SIMPLE: stalk
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stalk
<hw>Stalk</hw> <pr>(st⟦add⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stalke</ets>, fr. AS. <ets>stael</ets>, <ets>stel</ets>, a stalk.
See <er>Stale</er> a handle, <er>Stall</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The stem or main axis of a plant;
<as>as, a <ex>stalk</ex> of wheat, rye, or oats; the <ex>stalks</ex> of
maize or hemp.</as></def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The petiole, pedicel, or
peduncle, of a plant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which resembles the stalk of a plant, as the
stem of a quill.</def> <rj><au>Grew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>An ornament in the Corinthian
capital resembling the stalk of a plant, from which the volutes and
helices spring.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One of the two upright pieces of a ladder.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To climb by the rungs and the <qex>stalks</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A stem or peduncle,
as of certain barnacles and crinoids.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The narrow
basal portion of the abdomen of a hymenopterous insect.</def>
<sd>(c)</sd> <def>The peduncle of the eyes of decapod
crustaceans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Founding)</fld> <def>An iron bar with projections
inserted in a core to strengthen it; a core arbor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stalk borer</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the larva
of a noctuid moth (<spn>Gortyna nitela</spn>), which bores in the stalks
of the raspberry, strawberry, tomato, asters, and many other garden
plants, often doing much injury.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1401 pr=VMG --></p>

<p><ent>Stalk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stalk
<hw>Stalk</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stalked</conjf> <pr>(st⟦add⟧kt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stalking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>staelcan</ets>,
<ets>stealcian</ets> to go slowly; cf. <ets>stealc</ets> high, elevated,
Dan. <ets>stalke</ets> to stalk; probably akin to 1st
<ets>stalk</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To walk slowly and cautiously;
to walk in a stealthy, noiseless manner; -- sometimes used with a
reflexive pronoun.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Into the chamber he <qex>stalked</qex> him full still.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Bertran] <qex>stalks</qex> close behind her, like a witch's
fiend,⟦br⟧
Pressing to be employed.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To walk behind something as a screen, for the
purpose of approaching game; to proceed under cover.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king . . . crept under the shoulder of his led horse; . . .
⟦ldquo⟧I must <qex>stalk</qex>,⟦rdquo⟧ said he.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One underneath his horse, to get a shoot doth
<qex>stalk</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To walk with high and proud steps; -- usually
implying the affectation of dignity, and indicating dislike. The word is
used, however, especially by the poets, to express dignity of
step.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With manly mien he <qex>stalked</qex> along the ground.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then <qex>stalking</qex> through the deep,⟦br⟧
He fords the ocean.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I forbear myself from entering the lists in which he has long
<qex>stalked</qex> alone and unchallenged.</q>
<rj><qau>Merivale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stalk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stalk
<hw>Stalk</hw> <pr>(st⟦add⟧k)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
approach under cover of a screen, or by stealth, for the purpose of
killing, as game.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As for shooting a man from behind a wall, it is cruelly like to
<qex>stalking</qex> a deer.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To follow (a person) persistently, with or without
attempts to evade detection; <as>as, the paparazzi <ex>stalk</ex>
celebrities to get candid photographs; obsessed fans may <ex>stalk</ex>
their favorite movie stars</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stalk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stalk
<hw>Stalk</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A high, proud, stately
step or walk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus twice before, . . . ⟦br⟧
With martial <qex>stalk</qex> hath he gone by our watch.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The which with monstrous <qex>stalk</qex> behind him stepped.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act or process of stalking.</def></p>

<p><q>When the <qex>stalk</qex> was over (the antelope took alarm and
ran off before I was within rifle shot) I came back.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Roosevelt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stalked</ent>⟦br⟧
